Duck typing is a programming philosophy summed up by the phrase: "If it walks 
like a duck and quacks like a duck, then it's a duck."

In a duck-typed language like Python, what matters is not an object's type, but
whether it has the methods and properties you're trying to use. 

You never need to declare "this object implements interface X" — you just call 
the method, and if it works, it works.

This contrasts with statically-typed languages like Java or C#, where you'd 
need to explicitly declare that objects implement a method before passing them
to a function that expects such method.

The tradeoff is flexibility versus safety. 
Duck typing makes code concise and adaptable — you can pass any compatible 
object without boilerplate — but errors only surface when the code actually 
runs, which can make bugs harder to catch early. That's exactly the gap that 
the abc module fills: it lets you optionally add interface-like contracts when 
the flexibility becomes a liability.

The abc module (Abstract Base Classes) is part of Python's standard library and
provides the infrastructure for defining abstract base classes. It was 
introduced in Python 2.6 via PEP 3119.

+ What it provides

The module's core building block is the ABC class, which you use as a parent to
mark your own class as abstract. Alongside it, the @abstractmethod decorator 
lets you flag specific methods that any subclass must override before it can be
instantiated. 

You can stack over @abstractmethod with @classmethod or @staticmethod.

+ How it works under the hood

When you decorate a method with @abstractmethod, Python adds it to an internal 
set called __abstractmethods__ on the class. At instantiation time, Python 
checks whether that set is empty. 
If it's not — meaning some abstract methods haven't been overridden — it raises
a TypeError. This is a runtime check, not a compile-time one, which is an 
important distinction compared to languages like Java or C#.

+Beyond your own classes

The abc module also powers the register() mechanism, which lets you declare 
that a class is a "virtual subclass" of an abstract base class without actually
