## When you need super().__init__()
when the parent sets up attributes or logic that the child depends on. 
In your case, Stark calls super().__init__(first_name, is_alive) because 
Character.__init__ is where self.first_name and self.is_alive get stored. 
Skip it, and those attributes won't exist.

## When you can skip it
when the parent's __init__ doesn't do anything meaningful. Character calls 
super().__init__() on ABC, but ABC doesn't really set up anything. 
So technically you could omit it in Character and everything would still work 
fine.

